# NCS Documentation

> This file provides authoritative context for the ADU (the agent-based development system —
> i.e. you, the LLM) about the No-Code System (NCS) it operates within, and about the currently
> active Core-System. Read it fully before generating code, making architectural decisions, or
> answering questions about the system. Terms defined here take precedence over general
> assumptions.

---

## Purpose

NCS (No-Code System) is an LLM-powered Low-Code/No-Code platform that enables end-users
without programming knowledge to create dynamic digital Artifacts through natural-language
interaction. NCS consists of two parts, defined below: the **ADU** and the **Core-System**.
The ADU interprets the user's intent, generates the Artifact's source code, provisions the
Core-System's Base System{{#if coreUnitDescription}} (see "Base System" below){{/if}}, and orchestrates the
full deployment pipeline via the Core-System's Deployment Target. The user never writes or
sees code directly.

---

## Glossary

### No-Code System (NCS)
- NCS is the overall product: **ADU + Core-System**.
- The end-user only ever interacts with the ADU in natural language; the Core-System is fully
  managed on their behalf and never exposed directly unless the user explicitly chooses to.

### ADU (Agent-based Development System)
- The ADU is the natural-language-driven agent component of NCS — this is you, the LLM, when
  operating within this codebase.
- Its responsibilities are:
    1. **Intent capture** — understand what the user wants to build.
    2. **Code generation** — produce the source code for the Artifact.
       {{#if coreUnitDescription}}
    3. **Base System provisioning** — set up and configure the Base System for the Artifact
       (see "Base System" chapter below).
       {{/if}}
    4. **Deployment orchestration** — start, stop, rebuild, and update Artifacts on the active
       Deployment Target.
    5. **Iteration support** — allow the user to refine the Artifact through further
       natural-language instructions, resulting in code modifications and live updates (in
       Sandbox Mode).
- The ADU is targeted at end-users: people with no knowledge of web development, deployment
  infrastructure, or programming. All complexity must be hidden behind the ADU's interface.

### Core-System
- The Core-System is the infrastructure side of NCS, consisting of:
    - **Base System** — the pluggable backend an Artifact is built on (e.g. a CMS such as
      Directus). Described in the "Base System" chapter below.
    - **Deployment Target** — the infrastructure platform Artifacts are compiled, run, and
      served on. Described in the "Deployment Target" section below.
- The ADU controls the Core-System programmatically; the user never interacts with it
  directly.

### Artifact
- An Artifact is a digital application produced by the ADU.
- An Artifact consists of:
    - **Source code** — the generated files that implement the application (e.g. a web
      framework project).
    - **Metadata** — name and creation date.
    - **Deployment configuration** — one or more configuration files specific to the active
      Deployment Target (e.g. a Compose file, a Kubernetes manifest, a cloud run spec).
- An Artifact is always associated with exactly one Deployment Target.

### Deployment Target
- The Deployment Target is the infrastructure platform on which Artifacts are compiled, run,
  and served — the second half of the Core-System, alongside the Base System.
- The ADU controls the Deployment Target programmatically — the user does not interact with
  it directly.
- **The Deployment Target is selectable.** NCS is designed to support multiple Deployment
  Target backends (e.g. local container runtime, remote VM, cloud platform). The active target
  is determined by the NCS configuration, not hard-coded into Artifact source code.
- The deployment configuration files and operational commands the ADU generates are specific
  to the active Deployment Target. All target-specific details are encapsulated in the
  `.adu/deployment-targets/` templates (see "Starter Template and Repository Layout").
- Artifact source code itself must remain target-agnostic; only the deployment configuration
  layer is target-specific.

### Sandbox Mode
- Sandbox Mode is the **development runtime** of an Artifact — the mode in which it is
  actively built and iterated upon.
- In Sandbox Mode:
    - The Artifact is **running live** on the active Deployment Target so the user can preview
      it in real time.
    - The Artifact's **source code lives on disk** (on the host) and is made available to the
      running process, so file changes on the host are immediately visible inside the runtime.
    - When the LLM modifies source files, the running framework's **hot-module replacement
      (HMR)** or **dev-server watch mode** picks up the changes automatically — no full restart
      is needed for code-only changes.
    - If **dependencies change** (e.g. a new package is added to `package.json`), the runtime
      environment must be **rebuilt** before the change takes effect.
    - Sandbox Mode corresponds to the framework's own `development` mode (e.g. `next dev`,
      `nuxt dev`, `vite dev`).
    - There is usually an env variable set when the artifact is running in sandbox-mode, so that the artifact knows, in which environment it is running in.
      {{#if coreUnitDescription}}
    - The **Base System's services keep running** alongside the app process in Sandbox Mode,
      providing the API the frontend consumes.
      {{/if}}
- Sandbox Mode is distinct from a future "production" deployment, which would involve a build
  step and a production-optimized environment.
- The artifact under development is served behind a reverse-proxy that serves the artifact under `/sandbox/<technical_name>/`.
  Please make sure that whenever you set paths in the artifact, that you let the artifact set the path-prefix whenever it runs in sandbox-mode.

